[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the course! "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Hi to all chess lovers! I am Volodymyr Vetoshko, a GM from Ukraine, and I have prepared something very special for you in this Chessable Course ☺️ I firmly believe that in games with faster time control opening preparation is extremely important. If you are well-prepared and remember your lines, you get a nice edge } { (both chess-wise and psychologically) } { over your opponents from the start. You are going to spend considerably less time } { (which is a crucially important factor) } { during blitz and rapid games playing the positions you are familiar with. In the meantime, your opponents will be struggling to find a good setup against the tricky sidelines I will provide you with. The main approach in this course is to quicky deviate from the main lines into some less explored territory where we can outplay our opponents due to more knowledge and experience. You are going to get the same positions again and again, whereas your opponents will rarely face these lines and won't know much. I would also like to mention that all the lines in this course are perfectly sound and playable even in games with a classical time control. There are no lines where we are setting some dubious traps risking to end up in a worse position if our opponent avoids them. At the same time, there are a lot of hidden pitfalls our opponents can potentially jump into. Before every group of theoretical chapters I decided to include a small introduction to outline the key lines and ideas to make things easier for you. I have also did my best to explain the ideas, plans and strategic aspects of the positions throughout the course. Let's get started! } 
1.--   *

[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Four Knights Sidelines - 4...Bc5?"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  e5  
2.Nf3  Nc6  
3.Nc3  Nf6  
4.a3 $5 {[%csl Rb4]} { Our idea is to take the [b4]-square under control and prevent [Bb4]. If Black plays passively here d7-[d6], [Be7], [a7]-[a6], etc. - these lines can be found here our idea will be to push [d2]-[d4] and gain space in the center, avoiding well-known lines with [Bb4]. } 
{ One of the main points behind 4. [a3] is that... } Bc5 $6 { This at first glance looks quite logical and is a top-choice among amateurs, but runs into a thematic response: } 
5.Nxe5 $1 { A typical trick to remember in The Four Knights. } Nxe5  
6.d4  Bxd4  ( { This is the most common way Black plays in amateur games, but somewhat less bad is } 6...Bd6 { , which we will also cover in detail in Chapter 2. } ) 
7.Qxd4  d6  
8.Bg5  h6  
9.Bh4  ( 9. Bh4 { Followed by } 9...-- 10.O-O-O { and } 10...-- 11.f4 { is excellent for White. } )  *

[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Four Knights Main Line - 5...dxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  e5  
2.Nf3  Nc6  
3.Nc3  { In my opinion, this is a very good practical weapon for White because it can be used against both 2...Nc6 and 2...Nf6 and it almost forces Black to go for the 4 Knights opening. } Nf6 $1 { The best move for Black. } 
4.a3 $5 {[%cal Ga2a3]} {[%csl Rb4]} { Our idea is to take the [b4]-square under control and prevent [Bb4]. If Black plays passively here d7-[d6], [Be7], [a7]-[a6], etc. - these lines can be found here our idea will be to push [d2]-[d4] and gain space in the center, avoiding well-known lines with [Bb4]. } d5 $1 {[%csl Re4]} {[%cal Gd5e4]} { The best try. } 
5.Bb5 $5 {[%cal Bb5e8]} { Creating practical problems for our opponent by pinning the knight on [c6], making the [e5]-pawn vulnerable. Now Black has 3 logical options, the most natural of which leads to a large advantage for White! } dxe4 $2 { Looks natural, and many players who do not know this line will probably take on [e4] with a pawn. } 
6.Nxe5  {[%cal Be5c6]} {[%cal Bb5e8]} Bd7  { After this White trivially wins a pawn on [e4] after a few moves. } 
7.Bxc6  Bxc6  
8.Nxc6  bxc6  
9.Qe2  {[%cal Bc3e4]} {[%cal Be2e4]} {[%csl Be4]} Qe7  
10.O-O  {[%cal Bf1e1]} {[%csl Re4]} {[%cal Gc3e4]} ( 10. O-O { With } 10...-- 11.Re1 { next, winning a pawn on [e4]. } )  *

