6.Ne2  {[%cal Be2g3]} {[%cal Bd2d3]} {[%csl Re5]} { The knight is heading to [g3]. } Bd6  
7.d3  O-O  
8.O-O  {[%cal Be2g3]} {[%cal Bf1e1]} {[%cal Bc1d2]} ( 8. O-O { An important position. White scores pretty well in practice, since it is much easier to play here with White if you know the right plan! Please, note that the bishop on d6 is quite weak. White's plan should be to play } 8...-- 9.Ng3 { , } -- 10.Re1 { , and } 10...-- 11.Bd2 { with the idea to play } 11...-- 12.c3 { later, undermining the [d4]-pawn and opening the c-file for our heavy pieces. I prefer to preserve our light-squared bishop and not take on [c6]. Usually, the bishop steps back to c4, x-raying Black's king. } ) Ne7  {[%cal Be7g6]} ( { If Black anticipates Bc4 and tries to prevent it with } 8...Be6 { then we can simply play [Ng5] targeting the bishop } 9.Ng5 Bd7 10.Ng3 h6 11.Nf3 Be6 { and now we go for our [c2]-[c3] plan fighting for space on the queenside. } 12.c3 dxc3 13.bxc3 { , next [Re1], and [d4] are logical with a tension in the centre. } ) { 9...Bg4?! this allows us to get a bishop pair or advance on the kingside. 10.h3 Bh5 11.g4 Bg6 12.Qe1 (, preparing [f4], our queen will later go to [g3] or in some cases to [h4], with a nice edge.)} 
9.Bc4  {[%cal Rc4g8]} { The bishop has done its job. Now, [c4] will be a better square for it. } Ng6  
