{ Now we will discuss some dubious early sidelines that can be used as a blitz weapon against you. } 
1.e4  e5  
2.Nf3  Nf6  { If Black wants to play the Petroff Defence, the flexibility of our setup allows us to most likely transpose to the main lines of 4 Knights by playing... } 
3.Nc3  ( 3. Nc3 { Anticipating } 3...Nc6 { with a transposition, which will happen with a probability of around 90% } 4.a3 { transposing to the main line. } ) d6  { This is of course possible and leads to the Philidor Defence. But I find this move order unlikely to happen - if Black wanted to go for the Philidor Defence, he would start with 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 (. there I recommend 3.f3!? - you can find all the lines in this course in another chapter. Nevertheless, if such a move order happens, I suggest going for a simple setup:)} 
4.g3 $5 {[%cal Bf1g2]} {[%cal Be1g1]} {[%cal Bh2h3]} {[%csl Bd2]} {[%cal Bd2d4]} { Going for a kingside fianchetto, avoiding the main lines. Since this is a Blitz and Rapid repertoire, it would be good to force our opponent into unknown territory. So, I decided to give 4. [g3] as the main approach; if you like 4. [d4] more you can find it as an alternative line. } ( 4. g3 { We plan to go } 4...-- 5.Bg2 { , } -- 6.O-O { , } -- 7.h3 { and prepare [d2]-[d4] later; the rook will go to [e1]. It is quite a simple plan to follow. } ) Be7  
5.Bg2  O-O  
6.O-O  Nc6  
7.h3  {[%cal Bd2d4]} {[%cal Bf1e1]} {[%csl Rg4]} ( 7. h3 { Followed by } 7...-- 8.d4 { , and } 8...-- 9.Re1 { with a small edge. } )  *

