1.e4  c5  
2.d4  cxd4  { Anticipating some Smith-Morra Gambit. } 
3.Qxd4 $5 { This very rare move is my suggestion! As usual in this course, our main goal is to enter positions where we are going to have more knowledge, understanding, and experience than our opponents. As a result, your opponents, having faced something unusual, will start spending a lot of time - an invaluable resource in Blitz and Rapid games! } ( { I am pretty sure } 3.Qxd4 { will confuse Black. It is likely that this suggestion even confuses you at this very moment. One of the first rules for all chess beginners is to not move your queen out too early! However, chess is not always that straightforward, and, as you will see, an early queen's development has a lot of benefits and hidden ideas. } ) Nc6  {[%cal Gc6d4]} {[%csl Rd4]} 
4.Qd3  { The best square for our queen in this setup. It controls a huge amount of squares! It prevents [d7]-[d5] break, defends our [e4]-pawn, is ready to go to [g3] in some cases, and enables White to castle long faster in some cases! } Nf6  {[%cal Bd7d5]} ( { The following line } 4...g6 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.Nf3 Nf6 { transposes to the main line. } ) 
5.Nc3  { The right move to start with. We should prevent [d7]-[d5]. } g6  ( { The most common approach. Other moves, such as } 5...e6 { , } {5...d6 , 5...d5 , 5...Nb4 can be found here. } ) 
6.Nf3  {[%cal Bf1e2]} {[%cal Be1g1]} { Our goal is to quickly finish our development, castle and put the knight on [d5]. } Bg7  
7.Be2  O-O  
8.O-O  d6  ( { The advance } 8...d5?! { looks interesting for Black, but doesn't quite work: } 9.Nxd5 Nxd5 10.exd5 Bf5 11.Qd2! { . Now, [Nb4] is not even possible in this case. White is just a pawn-up. } {( If 10...Nb4 11.Qb3! and Black can't take the pawn on [d5] due to [Rd1] with a decisive pin on the d-file. )} ) 
9.Nd5 $1 {[%cal Bc2c3]} {[%cal Bc1g5]} ( 9. Nd5 { A very important move in our opening strategy! It creates tension in the middle of the board and forces our opponent to think whether to take on d5, kick the knight with e7-e6, or ignore. If Black ignores, our strategy will be to play } 9...-- 10.Bg5 { forcing Black to do something with his knight. It is also useful to remember that [c2]-[c3] is a good idea for us in general in our setup, taking more squares under control and restricting Black's dark-squared bishop. } ) Bg4  ( 9... Bg4 { A logical developing move. However, it doesn't create any concrete threat, so we can continue our plan with } 10.c3 { and } 10...-- 11.Bg5 {(immediate [Bg5] hangs the pawn on [b2] in some lines.)} ) 
10.c3  {[%cal Bc1g5]} {[%csl Bg5]} Nd7  ( 10... Nd7 (In this case compared to 9...Nd7 we are in time to play ) 11.Bg5 { and in case of an immediate } 11...Nc5 { , we can play } 12.Qe3 { . } ) 
11.Bg5  {[%csl Be7]} h6  
12.Bh4  g5  { We are happy to provoke [h7]-[h6], [Bh4], [g6]-[g5] since it will weaken Black's king. King's safety is extremely important in Blitz and Rapid! Sometimes the same position can be evaluated differently depending on a time control. Playing with an exposed king requires a lot of effort in faster time controls and there is a higher probability of missing some tactics. } 
13.Bg3  {[%cal Ba1d1]} {[%cal Bh2h4]} ( 13. Bg3 { Our next move is } 13...-- 14.Rad1 { . At the same time } 14.h4!? { looks quite tempting too. } )  *

