3.Bd3 $5 {[%csl Ye4]} {[%cal Bd3e4]} { An unusual idea in a well-known position. As a rule, in this course, I suggest less-explored options which, however, are quite challenging for our opponents to play against. As a result, you will most likely have a better knowledge of the lines, a better understanding of unusual arising positions, and more time on your clock after the opening : } ( 3. Bd3 { Our intention is to take back on e4 } 3...dxe4 4.Bxe4 { with our bishop and after } 4...Nf6 { retreat to [f3], } 5.Bf3 { , eyeing the [b7]-pawn, making it difficult for Black to develop his queenside. } ) dxe4  { This is the main line and the most logical response to 3.Bd3 . Other moves, such as 3...Nf6 , 3...c5 , and others will be analyzed here. } 
4.Bxe4  {[%csl Rc8]} {[%csl Rb7]} Nf6  {[%csl Re4]} {[%cal Gf6e4]} 
5.Bf3  {[%cal Bf3b7]} {[%csl Bb7]} {[%csl Bc8]} { The point! We want to make Black's development as uncomfortable as possible. } Be7  
6.Ne2  O-O  
7.O-O  c5  { Other moves do not make much sense - Black needs to gain some space and fight for the center. } 
8.Be3  { Attacking the [c5]-pawn. } cxd4  
9.Nxd4  e5  
10.Nb5  {[%csl Ra7]} { The most active response, attacking the [a7]-pawn. } Nc6  ( { If Black blocks f3-bishop before playing Nc6 with } 10...e4 { , after } 11.Be2 Nc6 12.N1c3 Bf5 13.Qxd8 Rfxd8 14.Rad1 { the endgame should be very slightly preferable for White. In the long run, White's goal should be to push queenside pawn-majority. Black's [e4]-pawn is blocked. } ) { After 12...a6 , the trade, 13.Qxd8! , is the most active move, trying to penetrate with [b5]-knight into Black's camp on the next move 13...Rxd8 14.Nc7 Rb8 15.Rad1 with a somewhat easier position to play. } 
11.N1c3  a6  {[%csl Rb5]} {[%cal Ga6b5]} 
12.Qxd8  Rxd8  
13.Nc7  {[%csl Ra8]} {[%cal Gc7a8]} Rb8  
14.N7d5 $14 {[%cal Gf3b7]} {[%cal Ge3b6]} {[%csl Yd5]} { With some pressure thanks to a centralized knight and active bishops. Later we can play [Rad1], centralizing the rook. }  *

