1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Qxd5  
3.Nc3  {[%csl Rd5]} {[%cal Gc3d5]} ( 3. Nc3 { Developing and gaining an extra tempo as a bonus. Now Black has a wide choice of retreats, the main of which are } 3...Qa5 { , } {3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8 . Others are rather dubious but can be used as a surprise weapon. } ) Qd6  
4.d4  Nf6  
5.Nge2 $5 {[%cal Bc1f4]} ( 5. Nge2 { Played with the idea to prepare } 5...-- 6.Bf4 {(. This is quite a rare move main move is 5. [Nf3] with much more theory and forced lines which I find suitable for Blitz and Rapid Repertoire - by simple means we obtain a pleasant position without a need to memorize long forced lines. Later we will move our queen out, go for [O-O-O], and attack on the kingside in most cases.)} ) c6  
6.Bf4  Qd8  
7.Ng3  {[%cal Be1c1]} {[%cal Bd1d2]} ( 7. Ng3 { Preventing Bf5. Next, we will play } 7...-- 8.Qd2 { and castle long, } 8...-- 9.O-O-O { . } ) { We do not play Ng3 in case of 5...a6 6.Ng3 because in that case, Black would play 6...Nc6 . } g6  
8.Qd2  Bg7  
9.O-O-O  O-O  
10.Bh6  {[%cal Bh2h4]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} { With an extremely dangerous attack. Our position is already close to winning. }  *

