[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "1) The Four Knights: Main Line"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

{ Hi to all chess lovers! I am Volodymyr Vetoshko, a GM from Ukraine, and I have prepared something very special for you in this Chessable Course : } { I firmly believe that opening preparation is extremely important in games with faster time controls. If you are well-prepared and remember your lines, you get a nice edge } { (both chess and psychological) } { over your opponents from the start. You are going to spend considerably less time } { (which is a crucially important factor) } { during blitz and rapid games playing the positions you are familiar with. In the meantime, your opponents will be struggling to find a good setup against the tricky sidelines I will provide you with. • The main approach in this course is to quickly deviate from the main lines into some less explored territory where we can outplay our opponents due to more knowledge and experience. • You are going to get the same positions again and again, whereas your opponents will rarely face these lines and won't know much. • I would also like to mention that all the lines in this course are perfectly sound and playable even in games with classical time control. • There are no lines where we rely on some dubious traps that risk leaving us in a worse position if our opponent avoids them. At the same time, there are a lot of hidden pitfalls our opponents can potentially jump into. Before every theoretical chapter, I decided to include a small introduction to outline the key lines and ideas to make things easier for you. I have also done my best to explain the ideas, plans, and strategic aspects of the positions throughout the course. Let's get started! } 
1.e4  { • The 4 Knights 1...[e5]. }  { • The Sicilian 1...[c5]. }  { • The French 1...[e6]. }  { • The Caro-Kann 1...[c6]. }  { • The Pirc / The Philidor 1...[d6]. }  { • The Modern / The Pirc 1...[g6]. }  { • The Scandinavian 1...[Nf6]. }  { •The Alekhine & Other Tries 1...[Nf6]; 1...[b6]; 1...[Nc6]. }  *

