3.Nc3  ( 3. Nc3 { Anticipating } 3...Nc6 { with a transposition, which will happen with a probability of around 90% } 4.a3 { transposing to the main line. } ) Bb4 $5 {[%csl Re5]} { This looks like reversed Berlin defense with an extra tempo for us. } 
4.Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Ye5]} { Accepting the challenge. } O-O  ( { The move } 4...Qe7 { was played once against me in an OTB classical game } 5.Nd3 Bxc3 6.dxc3 Nxe4 7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O d5 9.Re1 Bf5 10.Bf1 Qd8 11.Qf3 Bg6 12.Nf4 Nc6 13.c4 Nb4 14.Qb3 a5 15.cxd5 Nc5 16.Qc4 Nd7 17.Nxg6 hxg6 18.Rd1 Nb6 19.Qb3 Qh4 20.c4 Qe4 21.Bd2 Qc2 22.Qxc2 Nxc2 23.Rac1 Nd4 24.Bf4 { 1–0 } ) 
5.Nd3  {[%cal Rd3b4]} {[%csl Bc3]} { Forcing Black to give up a bishop pair. } Bxc3  
6.dxc3  Nxe4  
7.Be2  Re8  
8.O-O  Nc6  
9.Re1  {[%cal Bd3f4]} {[%cal Bc1e3]} { Next we are going to play [Nf4], [Be3] with a slight advantage thanks to a bishop pair. }  *

