4.g3 $5 {[%cal Bf1g2]} {[%cal Be1g1]} {[%cal Bh2h3]} {[%csl Bd2]} {[%cal Bd2d4]} { Going for a kingside fianchetto, avoiding the main lines. Since this is a Blitz and Rapid repertoire, it would be good to force our opponent into unknown territory. So, I decided to give 4. [g3] as the main approach; if you like 4. [d4] more you can find it as an alternative line. } ( 4. g3 { We plan to go } 4...-- 5.Bg2 { , } -- 6.O-O { , } -- 7.h3 { and prepare [d2]-[d4] later; the rook will go to [e1]. It is quite a simple plan to follow. } ) c5  {[%csl Rd4]} { According to the engine, that is the best move. However, to my mind, it creates a long-term weakness on [d5] and gives White a clear plan - we will try to occupy it with our knight. } 
