3.Nc3  ( 3. Nc3 { Anticipating } 3...Nc6 { with a transposition, which will happen with a probability of around 90% } 4.a3 { transposing to the main line. } ) d6  { This is of course possible and leads to the Philidor Defence. But I find this move order unlikely to happen - if Black wanted to go for the Philidor Defence, he would start with 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 (. there I recommend 3.f3!? - you can find all the lines in this course in another chapter. Nevertheless, if such a move order happens, I suggest going for a simple setup: 4. [g3].)} 
{ Of course, the main move is 4. [d4] and there is nothing wrong with it - if you have played this position before and you like it, you can stick to it. I will give some sample lines here: } 
4.d4  Nbd7  { In this case the simplest way to obtain a slight advantage is 5. [Bc4]. } ( 4...exd4 5.Nxd4 Be7 6.Bf4!? { I like this approach the most- we prepare [Qd2] and [O-O-O], followed by [f2]-[f3], [g2]-[g4], etc. That is quite a simple plan, suitable for Blitz or Rapid } 6...O-O 7.Qd2 { , preparing [O-O-O] } 7...d5!? { a tricky move. We should keep the tension in the center here: • After } 8.e5 { Black has } Nh5! { • And } {8.exd5 Nxd5 does not improve our position either. • However 8.Ndb5! starts the forced variation: 8...Bb4 9.O-O-O c6 10.Nc7 Nxe4 11.Qd4 Bxc3 12.bxc3 Qe7 13.c4 ± with the idea of meeting 13...Qa3+ by playing 14.Qb2 . } ) { 7...Nc6 8.O-O-O Nxd4 9.Qxd4 Be6 10.f3 , followed by [g2]-[g4], [h2]-[h4] and attack on the kingside. [Kb1] is a good prophylactic move after you castle long. White seems to be faster with his attack. } 
5.Bc4  {[%cal Bf3g5]} Be7  
6.O-O  O-O  
7.Re1  { A useful move. } c6  { Black is threatening [b7]-[b5]. } 
8.a4  ( 8. a4 { Preventing b5. We can push } 8...-- 9.a5 { later if Black allows, taking away the [b6]-square from Black's knight. I think it is quite a pleasant position with more space. It is easy to play with White. } ) a5  
9.h3  { Prophylaxis against a potential [Bg4] after Black moves the knight away from [d7]. } Nb6  
10.Bf1  { Other retreats, such as [Ba2] and [Bd3] are also possible. } exd4  
11.Nxd4 $14 { With more space and a clear target on [d6]. Next, we can play [Bf4], [Qd2], and [Rad1]. If Black plays [d6]-[d5], our typical reaction should be [e4]-[e5]. }  *

