{ In this chapter we will discuss some dubious early sidelines which, however, can be used as a blitz weapon against you. } 
1.e4  e5  
2.Nf3  d6  { This is rather passive and allows White to gain a space advantage. } 
3.d4  {[%csl Re5]} {[%cal Gd4e5]} { The most dynamic approach. Please, note that it is important to play it immediately instead of [Bc4] since in most cases we are going to castle long as quickly as possible. Our priority is to develop queenside pieces. } exd4  
4.Nxd4  Nf6  {[%csl Re4]} {[%cal Gf6e4]} 
5.Nc3  {[%csl Ye4]} {[%cal Bc3e4]} Be7  
6.Bf4  {[%cal Bd1d2]} {[%cal Be1c1]} ( 6. Bf4 { I like this approach the most - we prepare } 6...-- 7.Qd2 { and } 7...-- 8.O-O-O { , followed by } 8...-- 9.f3 { , } -- 10.g4 { , etc. That is quite a simple plan, suitable for Blitz or Rapid. } ) O-O  
7.Qd2  {[%cal Be1c1]} d5 $6 ( 7... d5 { A tricky move. We should keep the tension in the center here: after } 8.e5 { Black has } 8...Nh5! { , and } {8.exd5 Nxd5 does not improve our position either. } ) 
8.Ndb5 $1 {[%cal Bb5c7]} {[%cal Bf4c7]} { And here starts the forced variation: } Bb4  
9.O-O-O  {[%cal Bd1d8]} c6  
10.Nc7  Nxe4  
11.Qd4  Bxc3  
12.bxc3  Qe7  
13.c4 $16 ( 13. c4 { With the idea to meet } 13...Qa3+ { by playing } 14.Qb2 { . } )  *

