[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "Introduction to the Sicilian "]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  c5  
2.d4  cxd4  { Anticipating some Smith-Morra Gambit. } 
3.Qxd4 $5 { This very rare move is my suggestion! As usual in this course, our main goal is to enter positions where we are going to have more knowledge, understanding, and experience than our opponents. As a result, your opponents, having faced something unusual, will start spending a lot of time - an invaluable resource in Blitz and Rapid games! } ( { I am pretty sure } 3.Qxd4 { will confuse Black. It is likely that this suggestion even confuses you at this very moment. One of the very first rules for all chess beginners: do not move your queen out too early! However, chess is not always that straightforward, and, as you will see, this early queen's development has a lot of benefits and hidden ideas. } ) Nc6  {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gc6d4]} 
4.Qd3  { The best square for our queen in this setup. It controls a huge amount of squares! It prevents [d7]-[d5] break, defends our [e4]-pawn, is ready to go to [g3] in some cases, and enables White to castle long faster in some cases! } Nf6  {[%cal Gd7d5]} {[%csl Rd5]} ( { • Black is ready to push d7-d5, so we should start with } 4...g6 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.Nf3 Nf6 { transposes to the main line. } ) ( { • } 4...d6 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.Nf3 {(will most likely transpose to the main line where Black is going to fianchetto as [g6] is the most logical setup e7-[e6] weakens the [d6]-pawn significantly.)} ) ( { • If our opponent likes to play Sicilian-Kan or Taimanov Variation, } 4...e6 { , against the main line of the Sicilian, he may prefer to enter a similar pawn structure in this case, too. } 5.Nc3 a6 { restricting our knight. } {(5...Nf6 6.Bf4 transposes to the 4...[Nf6] line. )} {(5...Bb4 this leaves the [g7]-pawn hanging. 6.a3 Ba5 7.Qg3 forcing some concessions. Black should make some awkward moves to defend the [g7]-pawn. )} 6.Qg3! {(one of many cases when we make use of our early queen's development! Our queen is perfectly placed on [g3] - it targets the [g7]-pawn making it difficult for Black to develop his dark-squared bishop and putting pressure along the [h2]-[b8] diagonal especially the [d6]-square.)} ) ( { • } 4...e5?! { that just weakens the [d5]-square. In the Sveshnikov Variation, this move attacks a knight on [d4] which gives Black time to generate counterplay. Here it comes without any gain of time, which leads to difficulties for Black. } 5.Nc3 { now our goal is very simple - we are fighting to control the [d5]-square, which is a perfect outpost for our knight. } 5...Nf6 6.Bg5 { pinning the knight. Like in the Sveshnikov variation, it makes sense to trade our bishop for the [f6]-knight, eliminating the defender of the [d5]-square. } ) 
5.Nc3  {[%csl Yd5]} { The right move to start with. We should prevent [d7]-[d5], which would free Black's game. } g6  {[%csl Yg7]} {[%cal Bf8g7]} ( { The most common approach. Other moves, such as } 5...e6 { , } {5...d6 , 5...d5 , 5...Nb4 can be found in the Sicilian: Sidelines chapter. (5...e6 Black is trying to create a room for his dark-squared bishop. Also, Black's idea may be to play [d5]. Nevertheless, this move has a serious drawback - it significantly weakens the [d6]-square. That's why we play 6.Bf4!? ; this looks the most logical to me, trying to exploit the weak square on [d6]. Also, our threat is [Nb5]. Transposes to the 4...[Nf6] line. 6...Bb4 7.Nge2 (supporting the [c3]-knight. Next, we want to castle long and attack on the kingside by pushing pawns. It is also important to keed the [d3]-square for our pawn usually our pawn storm on the kingside requires playing [f2]-[f3], [g2]-[g4], [h2]-[h4]-[h5], etc)) (5...d5? doesn't work: 6.exd5 Nb4?? 7.Qb5+ +- Wins a piece. )} ) 
6.Nf3  {[%cal Bf1e2]} {[%cal Be1g1]} { Our goal is to quickly finish our development, castle, and put the knight on [d5]. Transposes to the main line. } Bg7  
7.Be2  O-O  
8.O-O  d6  ( 8...d5?! { looks interesting for Black, but doesn't quite work: } 9.Nxd5 Nxd5 10.exd5 Nb4 11.Qb3! { and Black can't take the pawn on [d5] due to [Rd1] with a decisive pin on the d-file. } ) { If 10...Bf5 11.Qd2! and 11...Nb4 is not even possible in this case. White is just a pawn up. } 
9.Nd5 $1 {[%cal Bc2c3]} {[%cal Bc1g5]} { A very important move in our opening strategy! It creates tension in the middle of the board and forces our opponent to think whether to take on [d5], kick the knight with [e7]-[e6], or ignore it. If Black ignores, our strategy will be to play [Bg5] forcing Black to do something with his knight. It is also useful to remember that [c2]-[c3] is a good idea for us in general in our setup, taking more squares under control and restricting Black's dark-squared bishop. } Nxd5  { In my opinion, this is already a concession. After we take with the e-pawn, the pawn structure reminds us of the one that arises in Accelerated Dragon lines when White goes for a Maroczy Bind and follows a similar strategy of putting the knight on [d5] and recapturing with the e-pawn. } 
10.exd5  {[%csl Oe7]} { It is important to understand the pawn structure that has just arisen. With our last move, we opened the e-file for our rook and fixed the pawn on [d6], claiming a nice space advantage. Now the [e7]-pawn is weak in the long run and serves as a target for us. It is usually not a good idea for Black to push it since after we take it, [d6]-pawn becomes weak. Additionally, we now have a pawn majority on the queenside and we can advance our pawns grabbing more space. } Nb4 $6 { Looks quite tempting, but can quickly lead to disastrous consequences for Black. } ( { The line } 10...Bf5 11.Qd1 Nb4 12.c3 { transposes to the 10...[Nb4] line. } ) ( { After } 10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.c3 { again is a useful move that restricts the [e5]-bishop and untangles our dark-squared bishop. Now we will plan to move the bishop to [e3] and start advancing the pawns on the side where we have a pawn majority - queenside. [a4]-[a5] is usually a good idea. This position is quite a simple one to play for White in fast time controls - our plan is simple and clear, whereas Black is struggling to find a good plan. Here is a sample line: } 12...Bf5 13.Qd1 Rc8 14.Be3 14...a6 15.a4 15...Re8 16.a5 { And later we can attack the [b7]-pawn: [Qb3], [Ra4], [Rfa1], [Rb4], etc. } ) 
11.Qd1  Bf5  {[%cal Bb4c2]} {[%cal Bf5c2]} { Black continues his aggressive strategy... } 
12.c3  Nc2  { It looks like Black has nice prospects, but all of a sudden... } 
13.g4 $18 { A brilliant trap to remember! We are deflecting the bishop from defending the knight. } Nxa1  ( { Doesn't help either: } 13...Be4 14.Ng5 { and bishop on [e4] has nowhere to go. } 14...Nxa1 15.Nxe4 +- { the [a1]-knight has no way out. After a couple of moves, we are going to take it and the rest is a matter of technique. } ) 
14.gxf5  gxf5  
15.Bd3 $18 {[%cal Bd3f5]} {[%csl Bf5]} {[%csl Ra1]} { Attacking the weakness on [f5]. There is no rush in taking the [a1]-knight - it is stuck and its fate is determined. }  *

