10.exd5  {[%csl Oe7]} { It is important to understand the pawn structure that has just arisen: • With our last move, we opened the e-file for our rook and fixed the pawn on [d6], claiming a nice space advantage. • Now [e7]-pawn is weak in the long run and serves as a target for us. It is usually not a good idea for Black to push it since after we take it, [d6]-pawn becomes weak. • Additionally, we now have a pawn majority on the queenside and we can advance our pawns grabbing more space. } Ne5  
11.Nxe5  Bxe5  
12.c3  ( 12. c3 { Again, a useful move that restricts the e5-bishop and untangles our dark-squared bishop. Now our plan will be to move the bishop to e3, } 12...-- 13.Be3 { and start advancing the pawns on the side where we have a pawn majority - the queenside: } 13...-- 14.a4 { , } -- 15.a5 { is usually a good idea. } ) ( 12. c3 { This position is a quite simple one to play for White in fast time controls - our plan is simple and clear, whereas Black is struggling to find some good plan. Here is a sample line: } 12...Bf5 13.Qd1 Rc8 14.Be3 a6 15.a4 Re8 16.a5 { and later we can attack the b7-pawn: } 16...-- 17.Qb3 { , } -- 18.Ra4 { , } -- 19.Rfa1 { , } -- 20.Rb4 { , etc. } )  *

