8.O-O  d6  ( { The advance } 8...d5?! { looks interesting for Black, but doesn't quite work: } 9.Nxd5 Nxd5 10.exd5 Bf5 11.Qd2! { . Now, [Nb4] is not even possible in this case. White is just a pawn-up. } {( If 10...Nb4 11.Qb3! and Black can't take the pawn on [d5] due to [Rd1] with a decisive pin on the d-file. )} ) 
9.Nd5 $1 {[%cal Bc2c3]} {[%cal Bc1g5]} ( 9. Nd5 { A very important move in our opening strategy! It creates tension in the middle of the board and forces our opponent to think whether to take on d5, kick the knight with e7-e6, or ignore. If Black ignores, our strategy will be to play } 9...-- 10.Bg5 { forcing Black to do something with his knight. It is also useful to remember that [c2]-[c3] is a good idea for us in general in our setup, taking more squares under control and restricting Black's dark-squared bishop. } ) Nxd5  { In my opinion, this is already a concession. After we take with the e-pawn, the pawn structure reminds us of the one that arises in Accelerated Dragon lines when White goes for Maroczy Bind and follows a similar-to-our strategy - puts the knight on [d5] and if Black takes, recaptures with the e-pawn. } 
10.exd5  {[%csl Oe7]} { It is important to understand the pawn structure that has just arisen: • With our last move, we opened the e-file for our rook and fixed the pawn on [d6], claiming a nice space advantage. • Now [e7]-pawn is weak in the long run and serves as a target for us. It is usually not a good idea for Black to push it since after we take it, [d6]-pawn becomes weak. • Additionally, we now have a pawn majority on the queenside and we can advance our pawns grabbing more space. } Nb4 $6 { Looks quite tempting, but can quickly lead to disastrous consequences for Black. } ( { The line } 10...Bf5 11.Qd1 Nb4 12.c3 { transposes to the } {10...Nb4 variation. } ) 
11.Qd1  Bf5  {[%cal Bb4c2]} {[%cal Bf5c2]} { Black continues his agressive strategy... } 
12.c3  Na6  { If Black sees our prepared trap just in time, the least evil is to just step back with the knight. Although, of course, it means that his aggressive strategy failed. } 
13.Nd4  Bd7  
14.Be3  Nc5  
15.a4 $16 {[%cal Ba4a5]} {[%cal Bb2b4]} ( 15. a4 { Followed by } 15...-- 16.a5 { , } -- 17.b4 { , etc. } )  *

