1.e4  c5  
2.d4  cxd4  { Anticipating some Smith-Morra Gambit. } 
3.Qxd4 $5 { This very rare move is my suggestion! As usual in this course, our main goal is to enter positions where we are going to have more knowledge, understanding, and experience than our opponents. As a result, your opponents, having faced something unusual, will start spending a lot of time - an invaluable resource in Blitz and Rapid games! } ( { I am pretty sure } 3.Qxd4 { will confuse Black. It is likely that this suggestion even confuses you at this very moment. One of the first rules for all chess beginners is to not move your queen out too early! However, chess is not always that straightforward, and, as you will see, an early queen's development has a lot of benefits and hidden ideas. } ) Nc6  {[%cal Gc6d4]} {[%csl Rd4]} 
4.Qd3  { The best square for our queen in this setup. It controls a huge amount of squares! It prevents [d7]-[d5] break, defends our [e4]-pawn, is ready to go to [g3] in some cases, and enables White to castle long faster in some cases! } Nf6  {[%cal Bd7d5]} ( { The following line } 4...g6 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.Nf3 Nf6 { transposes to the main line. } ) 
5.Nc3  { The right move to start with. We should prevent [d7]-[d5]. } g6  ( { The most common approach. Other moves, such as } 5...e6 { , } {5...d6 , 5...d5 , 5...Nb4 can be found in the next chapter. } ) 
6.Nf3  {[%cal Bf1e2]} {[%cal Be1g1]} { Our goal is to quickly finish our development, castle and put the knight on [d5]. } Bg7  ( 6...d6 { transposes to the main line with 6...[Bg7]. } ) 
7.Be2  O-O  
8.O-O  d6  ( { The advance } 8...d5?! { looks interesting for Black, but doesn't quite work: } 9.Nxd5 Nxd5 10.exd5 Bf5 11.Qd2! { . Now, [Nb4] is not even possible in this case. White is just a pawn-up. } {( If 10...Nb4 11.Qb3! and Black can't take the pawn on [d5] due to [Rd1] with a decisive pin on the d-file. )} ) 
9.Nd5 $1 {[%cal Bc2c3]} {[%cal Bc1g5]} ( 9. Nd5 { A very important move in our opening strategy! It creates tension in the middle of the board and forces our opponent to think whether to take on d5, kick the knight with e7-e6, or ignore. If Black ignores, our strategy will be to play } 9...-- 10.Bg5 { forcing Black to do something with his knight. It is also useful to remember that [c2]-[c3] is a good idea for us in general in our setup, taking more squares under control and restricting Black's dark-squared bishop. } ) Nxd5  { In my opinion, this is already a concession. After we take with the e-pawn, the pawn structure reminds us of the one that arises in Accelerated Dragon lines when White goes for Maroczy Bind and follows a similar-to-our strategy - puts the knight on [d5] and if Black takes, recaptures with the e-pawn. } 
10.exd5  {[%csl Oe7]} { It is important to understand the pawn structure that has just arisen: • With our last move, we opened the e-file for our rook and fixed the pawn on [d6], claiming a nice space advantage. • Now [e7]-pawn is weak in the long run and serves as a target for us. It is usually not a good idea for Black to push it since after we take it, [d6]-pawn becomes weak. • Additionally, we now have a pawn majority on the queenside and we can advance our pawns grabbing more space. } Nb4 $6 { Looks quite tempting, but can quickly lead to disastrous consequences for Black. } ( { The line } 10...Bf5 11.Qd1 Nb4 12.c3 { transposes to the } {10...Nb4 variation. } ) 
11.Qd1  Bf5  {[%cal Bb4c2]} {[%cal Bf5c2]} { Black continues his agressive strategy... } 
12.c3  Nc2  { It looks like Black has nice prospects, but all of a sudden... } 
13.g4 $18 { A brilliant trap to remember! We are deflecting the bishop from defending the knight. } Be4  { Doesn't help either: } 
14.Ng5  { And the bishop on [e4] has nowhere to go. } Nxa1  
15.Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Oa1]} { The [a1]-knight has no way out. After a couple of moves we are going to take it and the rest is a matter of technique. }  *

