3.Bd3 $5 {[%csl Ye4]} {[%cal Bd3e4]} { An unusual idea in a well-known position. As a rule, in this course, I suggest less-explored options which, however, are quite challenging for our opponents to play against. As a result, you will most likely have a better knowledgle of the lines, a better understanding of unusual arising positions, and more time on your clock after the opening : } { We intend to take back on e4 with our bishop, 3...dxe4 4.Bxe4 and after 4...Nf6 retreat to [f3], eyeing at the [b7]-pawn, making it difficult for Black to develop his queenside. } dxe4  { This is the main line and the most logical response to 3.Bd3 . } ( { This move } 3...Nf6 { and other alternatives are considerably worse than the main 3...[dxe4]. They allow White to achieve a better version of the main French defence lines: } 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Ne2 {(. We are not blocking the [f2]-pawn in some cases we will push [f2]-[f4] to add support to the [e5]-pawn and we are keeping the [f3]-square available for the other knight.)} ) ( { After } 3...c5 { White can get a small, but long-term advantage by simple means. } 4.exd5 exd5 { other captures are worse. } 5.dxc5 { entering a position where Black will have an isolated pawn on [d5]. } 5...Bxc5 6.Nf3 Nf6 7.O-O O-O 8.h3 { an important prohpylactic move to prevent [Bg4]. } 8...h6 9.Nc3 Nc6 10.Bf4 Re8 11.Re1 Be6 12.a3 Qb6 { . } ) 
4.Bxe4  {[%csl Rb7]} {[%csl Rc8]} Nf6  {[%csl Re4]} {[%cal Gf6e4]} 
5.Bf3  {[%cal Bf3b7]} {[%csl Bb7]} {[%csl Bc8]} { The point! We want to make Black's development as uncomfortable as possible. } c5  {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gc5d4]} { The strongest. } ( 5...Bd6 { This is not an ideal square for Black's bishop since it blocks the queen. } 6.Ne2 O-O 7.O-O c5 8.Nbc3 { Now we have an additional idea of [Nb5]. } 8...a6 9.Bg5! { Another point why 5...[Bd6] is innacurate. Black remains under pressure. } ) 
6.Ne2  Nc6  
7.Be3  {[%cal Bd4c5]} {[%csl Bc5]} { Adding support to our [d4]-pawn, attacking the [c5]-pawn at the same time. } ( { Taking the knight, } 7.Bxc6+ { , instead would be a positional mistake giving our opponent a bishop-pair and a possibility to play [Bc8]-[Ba6] later. } ) cxd4  { The most natural. } ( { A typical French move is } 7...Qb6 { , attacking the b2-pawn; but the good news is that we are not forced to defend it : } 8.O-O Qxb2?! { this by force leads to problems. } 9.Nbc3 { threatening } 9...-- 10.Rb1 Qa3 { followed by } 11.Nb5 { . } ) 
8.Nxd4  Ne5  { Other moves are significantly worse. } ( { The trade } 8...Nxd4 { is a concession. } 9.Qxd4 Qxd4 10.Bxd4 { followed by } 10...-- 11.Nc3 { , } -- 12.O-O-O { . Black struggles to develop his light-squared bishop. Our bishops are controlling two important diagonals. } ) 
9.Nc3  {[%cal Bd1e2]} {[%cal Be1c1]} {[%cal Bd4b5]} {[%csl Bb5]} ( 9. Nc3 { There is no rush with O-O. Our idea is to delay castling, play } 9...-- 10.Qe2 { next and in most cases go for queenside castling, } 10...-- 11.O-O-O { . } )  *

