3.Bd3 $5 {[%csl Ye4]} {[%cal Bd3e4]} { An unusual idea in a well-known position. As a rule, in this course, I suggest less-explored options which, however, are quite challenging for our opponents to play against. As a result, you will most likely have a better knowledge of the lines, a better understanding of unusual arising positions, and more time on your clock after the opening : } ( 3. Bd3 { Our intention is to take back on e4 } 3...dxe4 4.Bxe4 { with our bishop and after } 4...Nf6 { retreat to [f3], } 5.Bf3 { , eyeing the [b7]-pawn, making it difficult for Black to develop his queenside. } ) dxe4  { This is the main line and the most logical response to 3.Bd3 . Other moves, such as 3...Nf6 , 3...c5 , and others will be analyzed in the next chapter. } 
4.Bxe4  Nd7  { This looks weird - usually Black plays [Nd7] to prepare [Ngf6] when White's knight is on [e4]. But with a bishop on [e4] this preparation doesn't make much sense to me. However, I decided to include this move since it's a second } { (!) } { popular move in online database. } 
5.g3 $5 { An interesting idea - since Black gives us time, we can move our bishop to [g2] and then play [Nf3] getting a more harmonious setup. } Ngf6  
6.Bg2  Be7  
7.Nf3  O-O  
8.O-O $14 ( 8. O-O { This position reminds me of Catalan a bit where Black struggles with his light-squared bishop and White has more space. The game can continue: } 8...c5 9.Qe2 { , preparing [Rd1]. } 9...cxd4 10.Nxd4 { , followed by } 10...-- 11.Rd1 { , } -- 12.c4 { , } -- 13.Nc3 { , etc. } )  *

