1.e4  c6  
2.d4  d5  
3.exd5  { The Exchange Variation is my suggestion. In my opinion, that is a good practical choice since it does not require a deep theoretical knowledge compared to the Advanced Variation or Classical, our ideas and plans are easy to understand, and our development is quite simple and natural. } cxd5  ( 3... cxd5 { I would like to explain to you our strategy: we will try to restrict Black's light-squared bishop. • If Black plays } 4.-- e6 { when his bishop is still on [c8], that is awesome news for us! • If Black was to play here, he would most probably play } {4.-- Bf5 , so our next move is... } ) 
4.Bd3 $1 {[%csl Bf5]} { Taking the [f5]-square under control. The [g4]-square is also covered by our queen. } Nc6  {[%cal Bc6d4]} 
5.c3  {[%csl Bb2]} {[%csl Bc3]} {[%csl Bd4]} ( { Defending the d4-pawn, taking the b4-square under control and just creating a solid pawn chain. } 5.Nf3 { would not be good for our strategy since it allows } 5...Bg4 { . } ) Nf6  { Developing the knight and preparing [Bg4] on the next move. } ( { Developing the queen, } 5...Qc7 { , is another possibility. Played with the idea to prevent [Bf4]. } { An interesting idea is } 6.Na3!? { , implemented by many strong GMs! We are trying to take advantage of Black's last move and develop our knight with a dangerous threat of [Nb5]. } { • } 6...a6! { Black has to make this prophylactic move to stop [Nb5], otherwise he can find himself in a trouble. } {( • 6...Nf6? allowing [Nb5] is not a good idea for Black. 7.Nb5 Qb8 (Black has to control the [f4]-square, otherwise [Bf4] will give White a decisive advantage) 8.g3! preparing [Bf4]. 8...e5 trying to create some counterplay. 9.dxe5 Nxe5 10.Bf4 +- with an extremely annoying pin. Our threat is [Qe2] and, if needed, [Nf3], putting more pressure on the [e5]-knight. )} 7.Nc2 { knight has done its job, we move it closer to the center. } 7...Nf6 8.h3! { a part of our strategy is trying to keep the [c8]-bishop passive. We prevent [Bg4]. } 8...g6 { with the idea to play [Bf5] and trade his bad bishop. } 9.Ne2! {(preparing [Bf4] and keeping the [f3]-square free for a pawn it will play an important role as you will see later.)} ) 
6.h3 $1 {[%csl Bg4]} { Taking the [g4]-square under control. Now Black is struggling with his light-squared bishop. } ( 6. h3 { • If he plays } 6...e5 { , then we take, } 7.dxe5 { , and his [d5]-pawn becomes isolated. } {( • In case of 6...e6 the bishop on [c8] will be stuck. )} {( • The main approach is 6...g6 preparing 7.-- Bf5 (, but, obviously, [g7] is not the best square for Black's dark-squared bishop it will be restricted by our [b2]-[c3]-[d4] pawn chain.))} ) g6  {[%cal Bc8f5]} { Played with the idea to play [Bf5] next, getting rid of a bad bishop. } ( { • The move } 6...e6?! { blocks the bishop on [c8] and is too passive. White with simple play obtains a nice advantage. } 7.Nf3 7...Bd6 8.O-O O-O 9.Re1 { preparing } 9...-- 10.Ne5 { followed by } 10...-- 11.Bf4 { , } -- 12.Nd2 { , } -- 13.Ndf3 { and attack on the kingside. } ) ( { • } 6...e5!? {(definitely makes sense, but, to my mind, the arising position after a few moves is much easier to play with White especially in Blitz or Rapid since Black will have a long-term weakness on [d5] and a lack of obvious plan.)} 7.dxe5 Nxe5 8.Nf3 { the main move. White is trying to catch up with the development. The main drawback of this move is that White is giving Black a bishop pair, but Black's light-squared bishop remains restricted. } 8...Nxd3+ 9.Qxd3 Bd6 10.O-O O-O 11.Be3!? {(a good approach for Blitz and Rapid, trying to harmoniously finish our development we are preparing Nbd2.)} {11.Bg5 is the main move, but it by force leads to a position where Black has a lot of play. In faster time controls we should generally avoid positions where our king is not safe. ( As additional information 11.Bg5 is the main move, but it by force leads to a position where Black seems OK. 11...h6 12.Bh4 g5 13.Bg3 Bxg3 14.fxg3 g4 15.hxg4 Nxg4=)} ) 
7.Nf3  { We just continue our natural development. } Bf5  
8.O-O  { It is important to know that taking on [f5] is usually not a good idea for us since it gives Black nice attacking prospects. After recapturing with the g-pawn, the g-file opens for his rook. Black also obtains full control over the [e4]-square where he can place his knight. } ( { After } 8.Bxf5 gxf5 { Black will follow with } 9.-- e6 { , } 10.-- Bd6 { , } 11.-- Rg8 { , } 12.-- Ne4 { , } 13.-- Qc7 { and } 14.-- O-O-O { . In my opinion, White is in danger and it is not easy to create counterplay. So, we just castle and do not take any strategic risks. } ) Bxd3  
9.Qxd3  Bg7  
10.Bf4  { Improving our bishop before playing [Nbd2]. } O-O  
11.Nbd2  ( 11. Nbd2 { Our plan is to play } 11...-- 12.Rfe1 { and start pushing pawns on the queenside, grabbing space and creating potential weaknesses in Black's camp. } 12...-- 13.a4 { , } -- 14.b4 { , } -- 15.a5 { , } -- 16.Nb3 { , } -- 17.Nc5 { is the idea. It is easier to play with White when you know a plan. Black does not have a clear one. } )  *

