1.e4  g6  ( { I have to confess. Whenever I see my opponent pushing his pawn to } 1...g6 { early on, I get an uncontrollable desire to push } 2.h4 { , } -- 3.h5! {(Maybe, I watched too many games in the Dragon Variation, or Gruenfeld with [h4] from White's perspective... Nevertheless, this is not a bad approach at all! Playing [g6] Black creates a hook on the kingside, which immediately defines my strategy in Blitz and Rapid games sometimes in classical too: let's undermine it by pushing the Alpha-Zero pawn! King is going to stay in the center or we can castle queenside later. And that will be my suggestion: go for early [h2]-[h4], [h4]-[h5]!)} { At first, I wanted to recommend } {2.h4 , but Black turns out to have a good reply - 2...d5 , counterattacking in the center, which is a good approach vs a pawn-storm on the flank. So, we are going to prevent 2...d5 by playing 2.Nc3 first, and then ...-- 3.h4! I believe, it is going to be a surprise for our opponent and quite a challenge too. Also, it cuts off all Black's preparation : (1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.f3!? (I am happy to suggest you this approach! To my mind, it is a very practical weapon for Blitz and Rapid of course, it can be played in classical too. You avoid many theoretical lines compared to 3. [Nc3] in the openings such as Philidor Defence and Pirc. Our idea is to build a solid pawn structure in the center and in most cases play) 3...-- 4.Be3 , -- 5.Qd2 , -- 6.Nc3 and -- 7.O-O-O (. Another nice point is that it turns out to be quite useful to delay [Nc3]! Firstly, in some cases, you have an option to play [c4] and move the knight behind. Secondly, if Black starts some active play on the queenside c6 or [a6] followed by [b5], they have no target to attack since there is no knight on [c3]!) • 3...e5 4.d5 , a setup vs Philidor or Pirc, Claiming a long-term space advantage. Our plan is quite simple: 4...-- 5.c4 (an option available thanks to delaying Nc3,) 5...-- 6.Nc3 , -- 7.Be3 , -- 8.Qd2 , -- 9.Nge2 , -- 10.g4 , -- 11.Ng3 , etc. We can keep our king in the center. If you see a need, you can castle queenside and play Kb1 where the king will be safe too. This position looks like an improved version of Zaemisch System vs King's Indian Defence with an already closed center. ) ( • 3...g6 I like when my opponents play this move early on in Blitz or Rapid. It gives White a clear and easy attacking plan since the [g6]-pawn is a hook to undermine. 4.Be3 Bg7 5.Qd2 c6 6.c4!? gaining more space before playing [Nc3]. Also, it prevents [b5]. 6...O-O 7.Nc3 . ) ( I do not think that castling early is any good for Black, 5...O-O (. I feel like it is quite difficult to come up with a defence especially when you are short on time after White executes his main plan:) 6.Nc3 c6 7.Bh6 followed by 7...-- 8.h4 , -- 9.h5 looks scary for Black. )} ) 
2.Nc3  ( 2. Nc3 { Preventing d7-d5 and getting ready to push h4-h5. Black has no clue about our idea. Black will most likely anticipate } 2...-- 3.d4 { with a transposition to the main lines. } ) Bg7  
3.h4 $5 {[%csl Rg6]} {[%cal Gh1h8]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} ( 3. h4 { The main idea of our strategy. Black faces an unpleasant choice already on the 3rd move. It is not clear whether he should allow h4-h5, play } 3...h5 { himself, or maybe play } {3...h6 with the idea to meet 4.h5 with 4...g5? In any case, we will be ready for whatever he chooses. } ) h5  { This looks the most natural to me. Black is preventing [h4]-[h5]. However, now that [g5]-square is vulnerable - Black will not be able to kick our piece from [g5] by playing [h7]-[h6] anymore. } ( { • } 3...h6 { With the intention to play [g6]-[g5] after [h4]-[h5]. There is one important nuance to understand: after we play [d4], [Be3] and [Qd2], the pawn on [h6] will be under attack and Black will not be able to castle. } 4.d4 d6 5.Be3 Nf6 6.f3 { an important detail. Taking the [g4]-square under control is a part of our strategy. } ) ( { • } 3...c5 4.h5 { Now it is difficult for Black to develop his [g8]-knight. After [Nf6] our idea is to play [h6]. } 4...Nc6 5.Bc4 { keeping the tension on the kingside. No need to take on [g6] - Black will be happy to recapture with the h-pawn, trading the rooks eventually. Next we want to play [d3], [Nf3], etc. } ) ( { • } 3...d6 { it does not look reasonable to allow [h5]. After that Black is constantly under pressure. } 4.h5 Nf6?! { this allows } 5.h6 Bf8 6.d4 ± {( If 4...c5 5.Bc4 followed by 5...-- 6.d3 , -- 7.Nf3 with a pleasant edge. )} ) ( { • } 3...Nf6? { runs into } 4.e5 { and the knight has to go back to g8 since } 4...Nh5 { runs into } 5.g4 { +- } ) 
4.d4  d6  
