3.f3 $5 {[%csl Yf3]} {[%csl Ye4]} {[%cal Bc1e3]} ( 3. f3 {(I am happy to suggest you this approach! To my mind, it is a very practical weapon for Blitz and Rapid of course, it can be played in classical too. You avoid many theoretical lines compared to)} 3. Nc3 in the openings such as Philidor Defence and Pirc. Our idea is to build a solid pawn structure in the center and, in most cases, play 3...-- 4.Be3 { , } -- 5.Qd2 { , } -- 6.Nc3 { and } -- 7.O-O-O { . Another nice point is that it turns out to be quite useful to delay Nc3! Firstly, in some cases, you have the option to play } {3...-- 4.c4 and move the knight behind, 4...-- 5.Nc3 . } ) {(Secondly, if Black starts some active play on the queenside 3...c6 or 3...a6 followed by 4.-- b5 ,) they have no target to attack since there is no knight on [c3]! } e5  
4.d5  {[%cal Bc2c4]} {[%cal Bb1c3]} {[%cal Bc1e3]} {[%cal Bd1d2]} {[%cal Bg1e2]} {[%cal Bg2g4]} {[%cal Be2g3]} {[%csl Bd5]} {[%csl Be4]} {[%csl Bf3]} {[%csl Bg2]} ( 4. d5 { Claiming a long-term space advantage. Our plan is quite simple: } 4...-- 5.c4 {(an option available thanks to delaying [Nc3],)} 5...-- 6.Nc3 { , } -- {Be3 , -- Qd2 , -- Nge2 , -- g4 , -- Ng3 , etc. We can keep our king in the center. If you see a need, you can castle queenside and play [Kb1] where the king will be safe too. This position looks like an improved version of Zaemisch System vs King's Indian Defence with an already closed center. } ) Be7  
5.Be3  O-O  ( 5...c6 { trying to undermine the [d5]-pawn. } 6.c4 { of course, we should not give up our center that easily. } 6...b5!? { an interesting approach, advocated in 'Play the Power Pirc'. Black is trying to undermine our powerful center by sacrificing a pawn. } 7.Ne2!? { A nice antidote to Black's strategy. This move is not mentioned in the 'Play the Power Pirc' course. After Black takes on [c4], we want to move our [e2]-knight to [c3], and the [b1]-knight will eventually go to [d2]. } 7...bxc4 8.Nec3 Bb7 9.Bxc4 { we want to recapture on [d5] with a piece. White holds an edge. } { If } {8...cxd5 9.Nxd5! , then Black cannot recapture due to [Qxd5] and the [a8]-rook is in trouble. } ) 
6.c4  {[%cal Bb1c3]} ( 6. c4 { It is quite difficult for Black to create a reasonable counterplay here. One idea is to play } 6...c6 { , but we just ignore and after } 7.-- cxd5 8.cxd5 { nothing much changes. Another idea is to push [f7]-[f5] to get some activity on the kingside, but as you will see from sample lines in most cases it rather favours White. } ) Nh5  {[%cal Bf7f5]} {[%cal Be7g5]} ( 6... Nh5 { With the idea to play } 7.-- Bg5 { and prepare [f7]-[f5]. } ) 
7.Nc3  ( 7. Nc3 { The move } 7...f5? { doesn't work in view of } 8.exf5 Bxf5? 9.g4 +- ) 
{ In case of... } Bg5  
8.Bf2  ( 8. Bf2 { It is better to keep our dark-squared bishop. In general, it is not advisable to trade pieces when you have more space. Black still cannot play } 8...f5 { because of } 9.exf5 { followed by } 9...-- 10.g4 { with a fork. } ) ( 8. Bf2 { Next, we will push our kingside pawns: } 8...-- 9.h4 { and after the [g5]-bishop retreats to } 9...Be7 (if it retreats to 9...Bh6 then after 10.g4 followed by 10...-- 11.g5 it will be trapped - ) 10.g4 { , attacking the knight. After Black goes } 10...Nf4 { we are going to play } 11.Nge2 { trading his only active piece. } )  *

