[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "10) The Modern / The Pirc"]
[Black "2...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  g6  ( { I have to confess. Whenever I see my opponent pushing his pawn to } 1...g6 { early on, I get an uncontrollable desire to push } 2.h4 { , } -- 3.h5! { Maybe, I watched too many games in the Dragon Variation, or Gruenfeld with [h4] from White's perspective... Nevertheless, this is not a bad approach at all! By playing 1... [g6] } {(Black creates a hook on the kingside, which immediately defines my strategy in Blitz and Rapid games sometimes in classical too: • Let's undermine it by pushing the Alpha-Zero pawn! • King is going to stay in the center or we can castle queenside later. • And that will be my suggestion: go for early [h2]-[h4], [h4]-[h5]!)} ) ( 1... g6 { At first, I wanted to recommend } 2.h4 { , but Black turns out to have a good reply - } 2...d5 { , counterattacking in the center, which is a good approach vs a pawn-storm on the flank. } ) ( 1... g6 { So, we are going to prevent 2...d5 by playing } 2.Nc3 { first, and then } 2...-- 3.h4! { I believe it is going to be a surprise for our opponent and quite a challenge too. Also, it cuts off all Black's preparation : } ) 
2.Nc3  {[%cal Bh2h4]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%cal Bd7d5]} {[%csl Yd5]} ( 2. Nc3 { Preventing d7-d5 and getting ready to push h4-h5. Black has no clue about our idea. Black will most likely anticipate } 2...-- 3.d4 { with a transposition to the main lines. } ) c5  { Black may play this, trying to take the d4-square under control. However, now it transposes to not the best version of the Closed Sicilian for Black: after 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 g6 (is quite rare. I suggest forcing matters a bit - most likely Black won't know the lines since he opened with 1...g6 , playing the Sicilian was definitely not a part of his plan.)} 
3.d4 $5 { The most dynamic option. } cxd4  ( 3...Bg7 { this is not great but White should play precisely to obtain advantage: } 4.dxc5 Qa5 5.Bd2 Qxc5 6.Nd5! { a powerful move, putting Black into a difficult situation. Our threat is to go [Bb4] and after [Qc6] - [Bb5]!! For example, } 6...Nf6? 7.Bb4! Qc6 8.Bb5!! { and queen is trapped, [Qxb5] runs into [Nc7]+ } ) { In case of 4...Bxc3+ Black won't have a sufficient compensation: 5.bxc3 Qa5 6.Qd4! defending both pawns and targetting [h8]-rook. 6...Nf6 7.Qb4! Nc6 and [Nxe4] was a threat 7...Qxb4 (7...Qc7 8.Bd3 followed by 8....-- 9.Be3 and -- 10.Ne2 . ) 8.cxb4 Nxe4 9.Bb2 f6 10.Bd3 Ng5 11.O-O-O +/- With a clear advantage thanks to the bishop pair, lead in development, and more space. } 
4.Qxd4  {[%cal Bd4h8]} { Attacking the rook. } Nf6  
5.Nf3  {[%cal Be4e5]} ( { We want to push e5 next. Immediately } 5.e5 { is not working in view of } 5...Nc6 { . } ) d6  { This does not really prevent [e7]-[e5] and now we get an improved version of the main line. } 
6.e5 $1 {[%cal Be5f6]} {[%cal Bd4d8]} {[%csl Rf6]} 
{ The endgame after... } dxe5 $2 
7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  
8.Nxe5  {[%csl Rf7]} {[%cal Ge5f7]} Ke8  
9.Bf4  {[%cal Bf1b5]} {[%cal Be1c1]} ( 9. Bf4 { Looks pretty dangerous for Black. We are going to play } 9...-- 10.Bb5+ { followed by } 10...-- 11.O-O-O { next and Black is not able to finish his development in a normal way. } )  *

