3.d4 $5 { The most dynamic option. } cxd4  ( 3...Bg7 { this is not great but White should play precisely to obtain advantage: } 4.dxc5 Qa5 5.Bd2 Qxc5 6.Nd5! { a powerful move, putting Black into a difficult situation. Our threat is to go [Bb4] and after [Qc6] - [Bb5]!! For example, } 6...Nf6? 7.Bb4! Qc6 8.Bb5!! { and queen is trapped, [Qxb5] runs into [Nc7]+ } ) { In case of 4...Bxc3+ Black won't have a sufficient compensation: 5.bxc3 Qa5 6.Qd4! defending both pawns and targetting [h8]-rook. 6...Nf6 7.Qb4! Nc6 and [Nxe4] was a threat 7...Qxb4 (7...Qc7 8.Bd3 followed by 8....-- 9.Be3 and -- 10.Ne2 . ) 8.cxb4 Nxe4 9.Bb2 f6 10.Bd3 Ng5 11.O-O-O +/- With a clear advantage thanks to the bishop pair, lead in development, and more space. } 
4.Qxd4  {[%cal Bd4h8]} { Attacking the rook. } Nf6  
5.Nf3  {[%cal Be4e5]} ( { We want to push e5 next. Immediately } 5.e5 { is not working in view of } 5...Nc6 { . } ) Nc6  {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gc6d4]} 
6.Qa4 $1 {[%cal Be4e5]} {[%cal Ba4e8]} ( 6. Qa4 { Clearly best. We are ready to push } 6...-- 7.e5 { now, our queen is perfectly placed: it does not allow } 7...Ng4 { and also creates a potential pin after Black plays [d6]. } ) d6  
7.e5  {[%csl Rc6]} {[%csl Rf6]} {[%cal Ge5f6]} {[%cal Ga4e8]} dxe5  
8.Nxe5  {[%cal Ba4e8]} Bd7  
9.Nxd7  {[%csl Yf1]} {[%csl Yc1]} { Cannot say 'no' to a bishop-pair advantage : } Nxd7  { This looks a bit artificial to me. After... } 
10.Bb5 $36 {[%cal Ba4e8]} {[%cal Be1g1]} {[%cal Bf1d1]} { We got a very simple position to play: 9...-- 10.O-O , -- 11.Rd1 , -- 12.Bg5 , etc. We manage to seize the initiative. }  *

