1.e4  g6  ( { I have to confess. Whenever I see my opponent pushing his pawn to } 1...g6 { early on, I get an uncontrollable desire to push } 2.h4 { , } -- 3.h5! { Maybe, I watched too many games in the Dragon Variation, or Gruenfeld with [h4] from White's perspective... Nevertheless, this is not a bad approach at all! By playing 1... [g6] } {(Black creates a hook on the kingside, which immediately defines my strategy in Blitz and Rapid games sometimes in classical too: • Let's undermine it by pushing the Alpha-Zero pawn! • King is going to stay in the center or we can castle queenside later. • And that will be my suggestion: go for early [h2]-[h4], [h4]-[h5]!)} ) ( 1... g6 { At first, I wanted to recommend } 2.h4 { , but Black turns out to have a good reply - } 2...d5 { , counterattacking in the center, which is a good approach vs a pawn-storm on the flank. } ) ( 1... g6 { So, we are going to prevent 2...d5 by playing } 2.Nc3 { first, and then } 2...-- 3.h4! { I believe it is going to be a surprise for our opponent and quite a challenge too. Also, it cuts off all Black's preparation : } ) 
2.Nc3  {[%cal Bh2h4]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%cal Bd7d5]} {[%csl Yd5]} ( 2. Nc3 { Preventing d7-d5 and getting ready to push h4-h5. Black has no clue about our idea. Black will most likely anticipate } 2...-- 3.d4 { with a transposition to the main lines. } ) Bg7  
3.h4 $5 {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%csl Rg6]} {[%cal Gh1h8]} ( 3. h4 { The main idea of our strategy. Black faces an unpleasant choice already on the 3rd move. It is not clear whether he should allow h5, play } 3...h5 { himself, or maybe play } {3...h6 with the idea to meet 4.h5 with 4...g5? In any case, we will be ready for whatever he chooses. } ) ( 3. h4 3...Nf6? { runs into } 4.e5 { and the knight has to go back to } 4...Ng8 { since } {4...Nh5 runs into 5.g4 +- } ) h5  {[%csl Yg5]} { This looks the most natural to me. Black is preventing [h4]-[h5]. However, now [g5]-square is vulnerable - Black will not be able to kick our piece from [g5] by playing [h7]-[h6] anymore. } 
4.d4  d6  
5.Nf3  {[%cal Bf3g5]} ( 5. Nf3 { The most flexible. Black still cannot be sure whether we will play } 5...-- 6.Ng5 { or } 6.Bg5 { . Our main idea though is to play } {6.Ng5 and put some pressure on the [f7]-pawn following with 6...-- 7.Bc4 . } ) c6  { Also quite a typical approach. Black opens the diagonal for his queen and prepares [b7]-[b5]. Now I suggest a tricky move: } 
6.Bc4 $5 {[%cal Bc4f7]} { Targetting the [f7]-pawn and setting a small trap that can easily work in Blitz or Rapid. } Nf6  
7.Ng5  {[%cal Bg5f7]} {[%cal Bc4f7]} O-O  ( { If } 7...d5 8.Bb3 { followed by } 8...-- 9.e5 { . } ) 
8.Bb3  {[%cal Be1g1]} {[%cal Bf2f3]} {[%cal Bc1e3]} { A prophylactic move against [d6]-[d5] or [b7]-[b5]. White keeps the pressure. } ( 8. Bb3 { We can castle short, } 8...-- 9.O-O { play } 9...-- 10.f3 { , } -- 11.Be3 { , } -- 12.Qd2 { , etc. Also } 12...-- 13.e5 { is always in the air. } )  *

