1.e4  g6  ( { I have to confess. Whenever I see my opponent pushing his pawn to } 1...g6 { early on, I get an uncontrollable desire to push } 2.h4 { , } -- 3.h5! { Maybe, I watched too many games in the Dragon Variation, or Gruenfeld with [h4] from White's perspective... Nevertheless, this is not a bad approach at all! By playing 1... [g6] } {(Black creates a hook on the kingside, which immediately defines my strategy in Blitz and Rapid games sometimes in classical too: • Let's undermine it by pushing the Alpha-Zero pawn! • King is going to stay in the center or we can castle queenside later. • And that will be my suggestion: go for early [h2]-[h4], [h4]-[h5]!)} ) ( 1... g6 { At first, I wanted to recommend } 2.h4 { , but Black turns out to have a good reply - } 2...d5 { , counterattacking in the center, which is a good approach vs a pawn-storm on the flank. } ) ( 1... g6 { So, we are going to prevent 2...d5 by playing } 2.Nc3 { first, and then } 2...-- 3.h4! { I believe it is going to be a surprise for our opponent and quite a challenge too. Also, it cuts off all Black's preparation : } ) 
2.Nc3  {[%cal Bh2h4]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%cal Bd7d5]} {[%csl Yd5]} ( 2. Nc3 { Preventing d7-d5 and getting ready to push h4-h5. Black has no clue about our idea. Black will most likely anticipate } 2...-- 3.d4 { with a transposition to the main lines. } ) Bg7  
3.h4 $5 {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%csl Rg6]} {[%cal Gh1h8]} ( 3. h4 { The main idea of our strategy. Black faces an unpleasant choice already on the 3rd move. It is not clear whether he should allow h5, play } 3...h5 { himself, or maybe play } {3...h6 with the idea to meet 4.h5 with 4...g5? In any case, we will be ready for whatever he chooses. } ) ( 3. h4 3...Nf6? { runs into } 4.e5 { and the knight has to go back to } 4...Ng8 { since } {4...Nh5 runs into 5.g4 +- } ) h5  {[%csl Yg5]} { This looks the most natural to me. Black is preventing [h4]-[h5]. However, now [g5]-square is vulnerable - Black will not be able to kick our piece from [g5] by playing [h7]-[h6] anymore. } 
4.d4  d6  
5.Nf3  {[%cal Bf3g5]} ( 5. Nf3 { The most flexible. Black still cannot be sure whether we will play } 5...-- 6.Ng5 { or } 6.Bg5 { . Our main idea though is to play } {6.Ng5 and put some pressure on the [f7]-pawn following with 6...-- 7.Bc4 . } ) a6  {[%cal Bb7b5]} ( 5... a6 { A typical move for the Modern Defence. Black prepares } 6.-- b5 { . We have a clever way to meet this: } ) 
6.Ng5  {[%csl Rf7]} { Improving our knight, targetting the [f7]-pawn. We have exploited Black's move [h7]-[h5] in this way. } b5 $6 { Played in the spirit of the previous move. Nevertheless, after that Black is under severe pressure: } 
7.e5 $16 {[%cal Bd1f3]} {[%cal Gf3f7]} {[%cal Gf3a8]} {[%csl Ra8]} {[%csl Rf7]} { Threatening 8...-- 9.Qf3 double-attacking the a8-rook and the f7-pawn! Also, another idea is to push 9.e6 forcing some concessions. } Bf5  {[%cal Bf3f7]} ( 7... Bf5 { Shutting off the f-file for White's queen after } 8.Qf3 { . } ) 
8.Qf3  {[%cal Bf3a8]} {[%cal Bf3f7]} c6  
9.Bd3  { Trying to deflect the bishop from [f5]. } Nh6  {[%csl Rf5]} 
10.Bxf5  { The simplest. We are eliminating the defender of the [e6]-square. } Nxf5  
11.e6 $1 {[%csl Rf7]} {[%csl Ye6]} {[%cal Ge6f7]} { The point. After that Black's pawn structure on the kingside is destroyed. } fxe6  
12.Nxe6  Qd7  
13.d5 $16 {[%cal Be1g1]} {[%cal Bc1g5]} { With a close-to-winning position. Our knight on [e6] is extremely strong. }  *

[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "Introduction to Scandinavian"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays overaggresively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early Bg4 from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on } 2...Qxd5 { with his queen or play } {2...Nf6 intending to take later with the knight. } ) Qxd5  ( 2...Nf6 3.d4! { there is no need to try to keep an extra pawn. } {(3.Bb5+ leads to forcing variations, which is simply unnecessary, because eventually, Black is anyway winning the pawn back : )} {(3.c4 , in my opinion, is already a positionally dubious move: after 3...c6 4.dxc6 Nxc6 Black achieves a lead in development and a bright future. Our move is intending to gain extra space by controlling the center. )} { • } 3...Bg4!? { an interesting try to force matters and provoke [f3]. } 4.Bb5+!? { counterattacking. The consequences of 4. [f3] are rather unclear. } 4...Nbd7 { the critical move. } 5.Be2 { I believe this is the most practical decision! 5. [f3] leads to some complications and forcing lines which Black most likely remembers quite well, so I would rather avoid such complications in a fast time control game. } 5...Bxe2 6.Qxe2 { a typical recapture. The knight will go to [f3]. } 6...Nxd5 7.c4 { gaining an extra tempo and extra space. } 7...N5f6 8.Nf3 e6 9.O-O Bd6 10.Rd1 O-O 11.Nc3 ⩲ { With more space and a slightly easier to-play position. } ) { • 3...Qxd5 4.Nc3 Qa5 5.Nf3 Tranposes to the 2...[Qxd5]. } { • 3...Nxd5 4.Nf3 I prefer this over 4.c4 because in that case Black has an extra option of 4...Nf6 5.Nf3 and 5...c5!? 4...g6 5.c4! Nb6 6.c5!? Forcing matters a bit and creating real challenges for Black to solve. 6...Nd5 7.Bc4 our goal is to put as much pressure onto the knight on [d5] as possible. 7...Bg7 8.Qb3 c6 9.Nc3 O-O 10.O-O (10.Nxd5?! this gives Black counterplay: 10...cxd5 11.Bxd5 Nc6 ⇆) 10...Nxc3 Black has nothing better: 10...[e6] weakens the dark-squares too much. 11.bxc3 now our threat is to play [Ng5] with the idea to provoke ...[e6] and later exploit the weak [d6]-square. 11...b5! Black's best, preventing our idea of [Ng5]. But it severely weakens the [c6]-pawn. 12.Bd3 we do not need to take - after the text move, the c6-pawn remains weak. Next, we can play 12...-- 13.Bg5 , -- 14.Rfe1 , consider playing 14...-- 15.a4 , etc. } { 4...Bg4 this leaves the b7-pawn unprotected and we will immediately try to exploit that. 5.c4 attacking the knight and preparing [Qb3]. 5...Nb6 6.c5! the most direct. 6...Nd5 7.Qb3! and Black struggles to defend his b7-pawn. In case of 7...Bxf3 we are still going to take on b7, 8.Qxb7 . } { 4...Bf5 5.Bd3 the simplest way to get a pleasant edge. And the top engine line at the same time. 5...Bxd3 6.Qxd3 e6 7.O-O followed by 7...-- 8.c4 , -- 9.Nc3 with a space advantage and an easy-to-play position. } 
3.Nc3  {[%csl Rd5]} {[%cal Gc3d5]} ( 3. Nc3 { Developing and gaining an extra tempo as a bonus. Now Black has a wide choice of retreats, main of which are } 3...Qa5 { , } {3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8 . Others are rather dubious, but can be used as a surprise weapon. } ) Qa5  ( { • The most passive of the retreats is } 3...Qd8 { Black just wants to avoid theoretical debates, but this approach has a serious drawback - by simple means White gets a pleasant position with more space and a lead in development. } 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 { the main and the most dynamic move. } {( The move 5...Bf5 looks quite logical to develop the bishop before playing [e6]. However, White has a strong idea. 6.Ne5! threatening [Qf3] with a double attack on the [f5]-bishop and [b7]-pawn. 6...e6 (and now it is important to remember the following idea same as in the main [Bg4]-line:) 7.g4! bishop has no way back and we are trying to trap it and force some concessions. 7...Bg6 8.Bg2 again, as in the [Bg4]-line, taking the [e4]-square under control before pushing [h4]. 8...c6 9.h4 transposes to the main line with [Bg4]: 9...Bb4 10.O-O +- )} {( The move 6...Nbd7 would be a mistake because of 7.Qf3 , attacking [b7] and the bishop on [f5]. )} { After the mainline, } 6.h3! { would be a good move, clarifying Black's intentions. Now Black has an unpleasant choice: he can give up a bishop pair or retreat to [h5], which by force leads to terrible consequences. } 6...Bh5? { this by force leads to a terrible position for Black. } {( Objectively the best is 6...Bxf3 , but of course, White has nothing to complain about - a bishop pair and space advantage offer a long-term pressure. 7.Qxf3)} 7.g4! { a typical approach to break the pin in Scandinavian. } 7...Bg6 8.Ne5! { the point. We keep playing aggressively. Now our threat is [h4] with the idea to trap the [g6]-bishop. } 8...e6 9.Bg2 { improving our bishop and taking the [e4]-square under control before executing our main idea of [h4]-[h5]. The good news is that this move is attacking the [b7]-pawn and forces Black to react. } 9...c6 10.h4! -- 11.h5 { is a huge threat. } ) ( { • } 3...Qd6 4.d4 Nf6 5.Nge2!? {(played with the idea of preparing [Bf4]. This is quite a rare move main move is 5. [Nf3] with much more theory and forced lines which I find suitable for Blitz and Rapid Repertoire - by simple means we obtain a pleasant position without a need to memorize long forced lines. Later we will move our queen out, go for [O-O-O], and attack on the kingside in most cases.)} 5...a6 {(most of your opponents will take the [b5]-square under control by playing this or 5...[c6] preventing [Nb5], which is the main approach vs 5. [Nf3].)} 6.Bf4 Qd8 7.Qd3 { preparing [O-O-O]. [d3] looks like a more active square for our queen compared to [d2]. } 7...g6 8.O-O-O Bg7 9.h4 ± { and we are ready to attack on the kingside. } ) 
4.d4  Nf6  
5.Nf3  ( 5. Nf3 { The most natural. We are not afraid of the pin } 5...Bg4 { because it runs into a typical Scandinavian } 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 { idea as you will see later. } ) c6  ( { • The move } 5...Bg4?! { is dubious, but you should remember the following sequence to gain advantage: } 6.h3 Bh5 {( The trade 6...Bxf3 just voluntarily gives away a bishop pair. 7.Qxf3 c6 8.Bd2 with the idea to castle long and later go for a pawn storm on the kingside. )} 7.g4 { breaking the pin. } 7...Bg6 8.Ne5 { now that Black's queen is on [a5] we have some additional threats connected with } 8...-- 9.Nc4 { . } (another idea is to push 9...-- h4 - 10...-- h5 ) ) ( { • The other option } 5...Bf5 6.Bd2 c6 7.Bc4 e6 { transposes to the main line. } ) 
6.Bd2 $5 {[%cal Bd2a5]} ( { Less popular than } 6.Bc4 { , but that is a part of the reason why this is my choice : } {6.Bd2 is quite logical, breaking the pin and threatening some discovered attacks potentially. } ) Bf5  ( { After } 6...Bg4 { , as usual, we are going to ask the bishop a few questions. } 7.h3 Bh5 { keeping the tension which is, however, quite a risky approach. } {( The trade 7...Bxf3 is a concession, but probably more solid than the main line of [Bh5]. Of course, we do not mind getting a bishop-pair advantage : 8.Qxf3 Nbd7 9.O-O-O followed by a prophylactic 9...-- 10.Kb1 and later on 10...-- 11.g4 , -- 12.g5 , etc. offer a nice advantage. )} 8.g4! Bg6 9.Ne5 { threatening [h4]-[h5]. Our bishop on [d2] is doing a great job - the knight on [c3] is not pinned and, as a result, there are no moves like [Be4] or [Ne4]. } 9...Nbd7 10.f4! { threatening to trap the bishop on [g6] by playing [f5] and adding some support to our knight on [e5]. } 10...e6 11.h4 ± { and Black has no satisfying defence against } 11...-- 12.h5 { . We will either win some material or spoil Black's pawn structure significantly. } ) 
7.Bc4  e6  { And here I have found that one move scores significantly better than the rest in practice, which turned out to be quite an interesting idea! } 
8.Ne4 $5 {[%cal Bd2a5]} {[%cal Be4f6]} {[%cal Be4g3]} {(With a discovered attack on Black's queen. It looks like we just slightly changed the route for the knight main move is 8.Nd5 ) and our main idea is to take on [f6] anyway, but I have something else in mind to suggest when queen retreats to [d8]. ( The move 8.Nd5 is the main move played with the intention to take on [f6]. Our approach is different 8...Qd8 9.Nxf6+ Qxf6 10.Qe2 . )} Qd8  {[%cal Bd8d5]} {[%cal Bd5a5]} {[%cal Ba5d8]} { Queen went back to the initial square after drawing a triangle : } ( 8...Qc7 { a more active square for the queen, but now we are going to ruin Black's pawn structure which is a great achievement already - such a long-term advantage makes our position much easier to play and our opponent will have to spend more time than we will. His decisions are more difficult to make now. } 9.Nxf6+ gxf6 10.Qe2!? { I prefer going for [O-O-O]. I do not like an open file against my king in the Blitz or Rapid game, it creates unnecessary tension. I prefer to keep it safe. } 10...Nd7 11.O-O-O O-O-O 12.Nh4 12...Bg6 13.g3 ⩲ { taking the f4-square under control. It is important here, for example - after } 13...Nb6 { we can pin the knight with } 14.Ba5 { and there is no [Qf4]+. Also, there are some lines we can play [Bf4]. The bishop on [g6] cannot go anywhere and we can take it whenever we want - a threat is stronger than the execution. } ) { Taking the c2-pawn leads to a losing position by force: 10...Bxc2 11.d5! getting to Black's king. 11...cxd5 12.Bb5+! Nc6 13.Rc1 Bg6 14.Nd4 +-} 
9.Ng3 $5 {[%cal Bg3f5]} ( { Aiming at getting a bishop-pair advantage. That is how I decided to target this position in Blitz or Rapid. Going for } 9.Nxf6 {(requires memorization of dozens of forcing variations of course if you want to take the most from the position, which I simply cannot recommend for faster time controls - you will start consuming time, trying to remember a forcing sequence, and that is simply impractical. Why enter the lines that Black has probably played hundreds of times and has good experience in? We can claim advantage by softer means, and less forcing ones :)} ) Bg6  { A natural retreat. Now White simply got a much-improved version of the Classical Variation of Caro-Kann. And the approach is the same - let's keep creating problems for Black's light-squared bishop! } ( 9...Bg4 { this looks more active. However, now we simply get a bishop-pair advantage by force. } 10.c3 { defending the [d4]-pawn before playing [h3]. } 10...Nbd7 { In case of other developing moves, such as [Be7] or [Bd6], our approach won't change and we will play [h3]. } 11.h3 Bxf3 12.Qxf3 Be7 13.O-O-O O-O 14.Ne4 { with the attack on the kingside soon. Useful moves will be } 14...-- 15.Bd3 {(targeting the h7-pawn,)} 15...-- 16.Kb1 { , and a pawn-storm eventually. } ) 
10.h4  {[%cal Bh4h5]} h6  
11.Ne5  {[%cal Be5g6]} Bh7  
12.Qe2  {[%cal Be5f7]} {[%cal Be1c1]} ( 12. Qe2 { Threatening } 12...-- 13.Nxf7 { followed by } 13...-- 14.Qxe6+ { . } ) ( 12. Qe2 { If Black sees that and defends with } 12...Qc7 { , we will castle queenside, } 13.O-O-O { , with a large advantage thanks to the lead in development. } )  *

