1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Nf6  {[%cal Bf6d5]} 
3.d4 $1 ( { There is no need to try to keep an extra pawn. } 3.Bb5+ { leads to forcing variations, which is simply unnecessary, because eventually, Black is winning the pawn back anyway : } {3.c4 , in my opinion, is already a positionally dubious move: after 3...c6 4.dxc6 Nxc6 Black achieves a lead in development and a bright future. Our move is intending to gain extra space by controlling the center. } ) ( 3. d4 { After } 3...Qxd5 4.Nc3 Qa5 5.Nf3 { transposes to the } 2...Qxd5 { . } ) Nxd5  
4.Nf3  ( { I prefer this over } 4.c4 { because in that case Black has an extra option of } 4...Nf6 5.Nf3 { and } 5...c5!? ) Bg4  {[%csl Rb7]} { This leaves the [b7]-pawn unprotected and we will immediately try to exploit that. } 
5.c4  {[%cal Bd1b3]} {[%cal Bb3b7]} { Attacking the knight and preparing [Qb3]. } Nb6  
6.c5 $1 { The most direct. } Nd5  
7.Qb3 $1 {[%cal Bb3b7]} ( 7. Qb3 { And Black struggles to defend his b7-pawn. In the case of } 7...Bxf3 { we are still going to take on [b7], } 8.Qxb7 { . } ) Bc8  
8.Bg5 $18 {[%cal Bf1c4]} {[%cal Bb1c3]} ( 8. Bg5 { Pinning the e7-pawn and making further development quite challenging for Black. Next, we intend to play } 8...-- 9.Bc4 { and 10. [Nc3]. White is close to winning here. } )  *

