1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Nf6  {[%cal Bf6d5]} 
3.d4 $1 ( { There is no need to try to keep an extra pawn. } 3.Bb5+ { leads to forcing variations, which is simply unnecessary, because eventually, Black is winning the pawn back anyway : } {3.c4 , in my opinion, is already a positionally dubious move: after 3...c6 4.dxc6 Nxc6 Black achieves a lead in development and a bright future. Our move is intending to gain extra space by controlling the center. } ) ( 3. d4 { After } 3...Qxd5 4.Nc3 Qa5 5.Nf3 { transposes to the } 2...Qxd5 { . } ) Bg4 $5 {[%cal Gg4d1]} {[%csl Rd1]} ( 3... Bg4 { An interesting try to force matters and provoke } 4.f3 { . } ) 
4.Bb5+ $5 {[%cal Gb5e8]} {[%cal Gg4d1]} {[%csl Rd1]} {[%csl Re8]} ( { Counterattacking. The consequences of } 4.f3 { are rather unclear. } ) c6  { This Gambit line doesn't quite work for Black. } 
5.dxc6 $1 ( 5. dxc6 { Our queen is untouchable given } 5...-- 6.c7+ { . } ) Nxc6  
6.Bxc6+  { Simplifying the position since we have an extra pawn. } bxc6  
7.Nf3  ( { Now } 7.Ne2 { is worse than 7. [Nf3] in view of } 7...Bxe2 { and pawn on [d4] is hanging at the end of the line. In the case of } {7.Nf3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3 the [c6]-pawn will be under attack. } ) e6  
8.h3  ( { Usually, it is useful to include } 8.h3 Bh5 { for White. Later we will have an escape square of [h2] for our king. } ) Bh5  
9.O-O  Be7  
10.Qe2  {[%cal Bf1d1]} {[%cal Bc2c4]} {[%cal Bb1c3]} ( 10. Qe2 { One of the possibilities to consolidate. We prepare } 10...-- 11.Rd1 { and later } 11...-- 12.c4 { , } -- 13.Nc3 { etc. I cannot see any compensation for Black's missing pawn. } ) O-O  
11.Rd1 $16 {[%cal Bc2c4]} {[%cal Bb1c3]} ( 11. Rd1 { Followed by } 11...-- 12.c4 { and } 12...-- 13.Nc3 { . White is clearly better. } )  *

