1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Nf6  {[%cal Bf6d5]} 
3.d4 $1 ( { There is no need to try to keep an extra pawn. } 3.Bb5+ { leads to forcing variations, which is simply unnecessary, because eventually, Black is winning the pawn back anyway : } {3.c4 , in my opinion, is already a positionally dubious move: after 3...c6 4.dxc6 Nxc6 Black achieves a lead in development and a bright future. Our move is intending to gain extra space by controlling the center. } ) ( 3. d4 { After } 3...Qxd5 4.Nc3 Qa5 5.Nf3 { transposes to the } 2...Qxd5 { . } ) Bg4 $5 {[%cal Gg4d1]} {[%csl Rd1]} ( 3... Bg4 { An interesting try to force matters and provoke } 4.f3 { . } ) 
4.Bb5+ $5 {[%cal Gb5e8]} {[%cal Gg4d1]} {[%csl Rd1]} {[%csl Re8]} ( { Counterattacking. The consequences of } 4.f3 { are rather unclear. } ) Nbd7  {[%csl Rd7]} {[%cal Gg4d1]} {[%cal Gd8d5]} { The critical move. } 
5.Be2  ( { I believe this is the most practical decision! } 5.f3 { leads to some complications and forcing lines which Black most likely remembers quite well, so I would rather avoid such complications in a fast time control game. } ) Bxe2  
6.Qxe2  { A typical recapture. The knight will go to [f3]. } Nxd5  
7.c4  { Gaining an extra tempo and extra space. } N5f6  
8.Nf3  e6  
9.O-O  Bd6  
10.Rd1  O-O  
11.Nc3 $14 { With more space and a slightly easier-to-play position. }  *

[Event " Rapid and Blitz 1.e4 Repertoire"]
[White "11) The Scandinavian"]
[Black "2...Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qe5+ #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]

1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Qxd5  
3.Nc3  {[%csl Rd5]} {[%cal Gc3d5]} ( 3. Nc3 { Developing and gaining an extra tempo as a bonus. Now Black has a wide choice of retreats, the main of which are } 3...Qa5 { , } {3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8 . Others are rather dubious but can be used as a surprise weapon. } ) Qe5+ $5 {[%csl Re1]} {[%cal Ge5e1]} { This is also objectively quite a dubious way of playing and I would definitely mark it as at least a dubious one if it was a Classical time control game, but here I marked it an interesting move because this course is about the Opening Repertoire for Blitz and Rapid, and this check can be used in Blitz to surprise the opponent. I played it myself in Titled Tuesdays a couple of times, and I even managed to make a draw vs Levon Aronian in this line with Black. However, if White knows a few things about this line, the opening will most likely turn into a disaster for Black. } 
4.Be2  Bg4  { The point ot a previous play. } 
5.d4  { Other moves give considerably less. } Bxe2  
6.Ngxe2  Qa5  
7.O-O  Nf6  ( 7... Nf6 { The key point in this position one needs to understand: White should play aggressively! We have a clear lead in development, and if we make several 'normal' developing moves from general considerations, our dynamic advantage will most likely evaporate. We need to transform our dynamic advantage into something visible: material gain, Black's spoiled pawn structure, etc. One idea is to push } 8.b4 { immediately harassing the black queen, but then after } 8...Qh5 { requires memorization of a few forcing lines. } ) ( 7... Nf6 { My suggestion is to go for the idea of playing } 8.d5! (making Black's development rather uncomfortable, and interfering with the access of black queen to [h5] we keep the 8. [b4] idea in mind.) ) 
8.d5 $5 {[%cal Ba5h5]} {[%csl Bd5]} g6  
9.b4 $1 { Typical for this line. } Qxb4  
10.Rb1 $16 {[%cal Bb1b7]} { After which the [b7]-pawn falls and Black is in trouble. }  *

