1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Qxd5  
3.Nc3  {[%csl Rd5]} {[%cal Gc3d5]} ( 3. Nc3 { Developing and gaining an extra tempo as a bonus. Now Black has a wide choice of retreats, the main of which are } 3...Qa5 { , } {3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8 . Others are rather dubious but can be used as a surprise weapon. } ) Qd8  { The most passive of the retreats. Black just wants to avoid theoretical debates, but this approach has a serious drawback - by simple means White gets a pleasant position with more space and a lead in development. } 
4.d4  Nf6  
5.Nf3  Bf5  { It looks quite logical to develop the bishop before playing [e7]-[e6]. However, White has a strong idea. } 
6.Ne5 $1 {[%cal Bd1f3]} {[%cal Bf3f5]} {[%cal Bf3b7]} ( 6. Ne5 { Threatening } 6...-- 7.Qf3 { with a double attack on the [f5]-bishop and [b7]-pawn. } ) e6  ( {(And now it is important to remember the following idea same as in the main Bg4-line: the developing move)} 6...Nbd7 { , would be a mistake because of } 7.Qf3 { , attacking [b7]-pawn and [f5]-bishop. } ) 
7.g4 $1 { Bishop has no way back and we are trying to trap it and force some concessions. } Bg6  
8.Bg2  {[%cal Bg2b7]} { Again, as in the Bg4-line, taking the [e4]-square under control before pushing [h2]-[h4]. } c6  
9.h4  { Transposes to the main line with Bg4. } Bb4  
10.O-O $18 {[%cal Bh4h5]}  *

