1.e4  d5  { The Scandinavian! This opening can be seen in Blitz or Rapid quite often since it avoids a lot of theory by cutting off multiple options that White has in other openings. Usually, it leads to more or less similar positions and does not require that much knowledge. A clear drawback is that White gets a lead in development very early. Also, if Black plays over aggressively later on White can try to punish him. I am mainly talking about the lines with an early [Bg4] from Black which are objectively bad for Black, but require some precision from White. } 
2.exd5  ( 2. exd5 { The only good move in this position. Now Black has a choice: he can either take on d5 with his queen, } 2...Qxd5 { or play } {2...Nf6 , intending to take later with the knight. } ) Qxd5  
3.Nc3  {[%csl Rd5]} {[%cal Gc3d5]} ( 3. Nc3 { Developing and gaining an extra tempo as a bonus. Now Black has a wide choice of retreats, the main of which are } 3...Qa5 { , } {3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8 . Others are rather dubious but can be used as a surprise weapon. } ) Qd8  { The most passive of the retreats. Black just wants to avoid theoretical debates, but this approach has a serious drawback - by simple means White gets a pleasant position with more space and a lead in development. } 
4.d4  Nf6  
5.Nf3  Bg4  {[%csl Rf3]} {[%cal Gg4d1]} { The main and the most dynamic move. } ( { The advance } 5...e6 { looks rather passive, it blocks the c8-bishop. White can seize the initiative by simple means: } 6.Bg5 Be7 7.Bd3 O-O 8.Qe2 { , getting ready to castle long and start an attack on the kingside. } 8...h6 9.h4 { a typical pattern to keep the tension, the bishop is poisoned since after } 9...hxg5 10.hxg5 { the rook comes into play with a decisive effect. Black is not able to survive here. } ) 
6.h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4]} ( 6. h3 { Clarifying Black's intentions. Now Black has an unpleasant choice: he can give up a bishop pair, } 6...Bxf3 { or retreat to [h5], } {6...Bh5 which by force leads to terrible consequences. } ) Bxf3  { That is objectively best, but of course White has nothing to complain about - a bishop pair and space advantage offer a long-term pressure. } 
7.Qxf3  {[%csl Rb7]} {[%cal Gf3b7]} c6  ( { Black cannot capture on d4, } 7...Qxd4 { in view of } 8.Qxb7 { . } ) 
8.Be3  { Defending the [d4]-pawn. } e6  
9.a3  ( { If a position allows, I prefer not to give my opponent even a shadow of activity. } 9.a3 { prevents [Bb4]. Since we have a lead in development and more space, our intention will be to go for } 9...-- 10.O-O-O { which looks challenging for Black. So, if we allow [Bb4] we can forget about castling long. That is why I like this small prophylactic measure. } ) Nbd7  
10.O-O-O  Bd6  
11.Kb1 $16 {[%cal Bg2g4]} {[%cal Bg4g5]} {[%cal Bh3h4]} {[%cal Bh4h5]} {[%cal Bg5g6]} ( 11. Kb1 { A typical useful move in general after we castle queenside. Our plan is to advance on the kingside by pushing } 11...-- 12.g4 { , } -- 13.g5 { , } -- 14.h4 { , } -- 15.h5 { , etc. trying to destroy Black's refutes. A bishop pair, space advantage, and a clear plan give us a much better middlegame. } )  *

