space and Black's position looks too passive. )} {( 1...Nc6 this is not a popular move but still can be seen in Blitz games from time to time. Our approach against it will be quite simple. 2.Nf3 there is no need to study theory after 2. [d4] [d5]. We want to transpose the 4-Knights variation if Black goes 2...[e5]. 2...d6 (2...e5 3.Nc3 transposing to the chapter with 4 Knights vs 1...[e5]. ) 3.h3 the simplest, yet quite strong. We prevent all possible counterplay and get ready to push [d4]. 3...Nf6 4.Nc3 ⩲ We will play [d4] next with a nice edge. That is even an improved version of 4-Knights for us, because, first of all, Black has already committed to ...[d6] and blocked his [f8]-bishop, and secondly we played [h2]-[h3] preventing [Bg4] which is quite useful. )} ) 
